dsDescriptionValue.value: This collection of files is from longitudinal studies conducted by the Institute of Nutrition of central America and Panama (INCAP), between 1969 and 1977. The studies focused on the physical and psychological development in pre-school aged children in rural Guatemala. The purpose was to investigate the impact of mild to moderate malnutrition on physical and mental growth and development in pre-school aged (0-7 years old) children in rural Guatemala.

fields.value:
The sample consists of selected children in four rural Spanish-speaking villages of Eastern Guatemala, two larger villages of about 850 persons each and two smaller ones of about 500 persons each. The criteria of child selection are that the child's birth date be known with "confidence", that the child be born before 1 March 1973, and that the child be observed during the study period at least once from birth to 84 months of age in any of the study villages, but began 1 January 1969 for the two larger villages (03 and 06) and 1 May 1969 for the two smaller (08 and 14).

The villages were originally selected as two matched pairs, the two larger villages forming a matched pair and two smaller another matched pair. The matching was considered approximate; significant differences occurred between village sizes on so-called baseline measures, while no significant or important differences appeared within pairs.

The villages chosen for inclusion in the study were screened from a very large pool of candidates in an effort to achieve as much homogeneity as possible amongst the final study villages. Because of budget limitations and differences in required type of respondents, different instruments were surveyed on different overlapping samples in six communities

Further details can be found in the document titled Documentation of INCAP's Longitudinal Data Files (November 1980 version) and in the Codebook and Users's Manual by Henry L. Corona, prepared in August 1978.
The data were collected in 14 survey instruments.

These files are cleaned, reorganized versions of files originally created in INCAP in Guatemala. In 1979 it was found that a) errors and out-of-range codes appeared in the files and b) there was no systematic way to specify who was in the village at any one time (in order to determine sample eligibility). During 1980, the files were reorganized into relational form and cleaned. Wild codes, inconsisten information between files, summary variables attributed to incorrect age periods, outliers, etc. wre checked and reconciled using the original data, when available, and/or other checks within the data, when possible.
